- flashsystem-tempest-dsvm-full-fc http://dal05.objectstorage.softlayer.net/v1/AUTH_0bd27569-6310-44fc-8a8d-36a112cac4ec/IBM-STORAGE-CI/flashsystem-tempest-dsvm-full-fc/6191 : SUCCESS in 1h 49m 46s'}, {'account_id': 21976, 'date': '2018-03-13 00:26:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build succeeded.

- kaminario-dsvm-tempest-full-iscsi http://54.209.116.144/31/552131/1/check/kaminario-dsvm-tempest-full-iscsi/6832571 : SUCCESS in 1h 33m 08s
- kaminario-dsvm-tempest-full-FC http://54.209.116.144/31/552131/1/check/kaminario-dsvm-tempest-full-FC/6f3f854 : SUCCESS in 1h 29m 04s'}, {'account_id': 7012, 'date': '2018-03-13 10:59:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Eric: I was looking at the tests that are run by lio-barbican (see start here: http://logs.openstack.org/31/552131/1/check/cinder-tempest-dsvm-lvm-lio-barbican/9d4966d/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-03-12_21_11_25_952990 ) and there are several tempest tests for volume encryption that it doesn't run, such as https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/scenario/test_encrypted_cinder_volumes.py -- as far as I can tell, the only tests that are run that are directly related to volume encryption are http://logs.openstack.org/31/552131/1/check/cinder-tempest-dsvm-lvm-lio-barbican/9d4966d/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-03-12_21_35_58_377000 , which confirms an encrypted volume type can be created, and http://logs.openstack.org/31/552131/1/check/cinder-tempest-dsvm-lvm-lio-barbican/9d4966d/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-03-12_21_45_06_265694 , which confirms booting can happen from a volume.

However, I might be missing something.  If the lio-barbican test does in fact test the full path for an encrypted volume being attached to and detached from an instance, then the barbican-tempest-plugin tests aren't needed."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2018-03-13 14:55:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The intent of the existing barbican job is to run full volume encryption tests.

It does run
    tempest.scenario.test_volume_boot_pattern.TestVolumeBootPattern.test_boot_server_from_encrypted_volume_luks

But it looks like you are right that it isn't running the scenario.test_encrypted_cinder_volumes test.

I'll try turning that on."}, {'account_id': 7012, 'date': '2018-03-15 15:46:25.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Encryption tests are already being run in cinder-tempest-dvsm-lvm-li-barbican, and so the barbican-tempest-plugin tests won't be needed unless image signature verification is added to cinder.

See http://logs.openstack.org/41/552541/1/check/cinder-tempest-dsvm-lvm-lio-barbican/c199841/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-03-13_17_55_26_929671 for an example of a test that will be run with barbican as a backend that will test the same functionality."}]

commit_message:
Add barbican-tempest experimental job

The barbican-tempest-plugin has tests for
volume encryption, which uses cinder. This
patch adds the barbican-tempest-plugin tests
to the cinder experimental zuulv3 jobs, so
that it can be run against patches that
might affect volume encryption functionality.

Change-Id: If30a4c91134153de02508bae8391eb7014eb1b8b

IMO the problem with BIOS configuration is more complex that described in the spec. You propose configuration as part of manual cleaning. The problems are 1) we can use current manual cleaning mechanism 2) BIOS configuration usually is low-cost operation, only node restart is needed in general case for applying. Why operator can not tune options in active state and then restart the node via API? Or during deploying? 3) Some options (power limits for example) can be applied on the fly without restart. Why not change these options in the active state? 4) Many BIOS configurations options is vendor-specific. Do you propose to change only generic options, or also vendor-specific? Makes sense to have generic options identical. You can look my abandoned spec with the same proposal, it is overcomplex.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-08-25 08:11:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yuriy, starting with manual cleaning steps is a good idea to me, because that's the framework we have for running vendor-specific actions and reporting their status.

Your comments about it being fast are not quite correct, because you note yourself that 1. it may not be always the case, 2. setting configuration may need a restart (or several). This is exactly the use case we have for manual cleaning. Even several fast actions (like updating iLO firmware) are implemented this way already. And this is ignoring the fact that some vendors or operators may want have configuration that is applied in-band.

Also, you comment imply that we can have a synchronous API that sets this configuration. We should never have synchronous API that calls into BMCs (again, ignoring potential in-band configuration).

As to standardizing the properties, I would love that, but I've given up on it since we last talked :( Too many vendor options, too many things that can be considered BIOS configuration.

As to setting BIOS configuration for active/deploying nodes, I guess it requires interaction with Nova. We failed to agree on a way to pass such things so far.

So, without reading this spec (I'm on leave today), I think manual cleaning is the way to go here."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-08-25 08:18:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Ruby & Mark, thanks for your comments again!

I did few changes according to our discussion:
1) do a full sync of cached bios settings everytime the bios config cleaning step is called.
2) noted that calling bios cleaning step with an empty dict argument will also trigger the updating of current bios settings in db.
3) explicitly describe the format of 'settings' field for NodeBIOS object.

wrt the function name of 'cache_bios_properties', I don't think we have a strong reason to change it other than keeping as it is, but welcome any further comments or proposals to the name.

I guess I'm lacking clarity on if this is intended to be purely an interface only supported in out of band use, or it could be an in-band mechanism to be used with hardware where supported. commit_message:
Add HW_NIC_SRIOV_TRUSTED trait

Adds a new trait to indicate whether all VFs on a PF or a single VF on a
PF is "trusted" and therefore able to operate in promiscuous mode.

Change-Id: If9d4af6ae7158ff8bcab6cdcd979145af307ce84

commit_message:
Add LDAP-backed domain gate

This patch set adds a nv-gating with an OpenLDAP server with some sample
data loaded for development or testing use using a bootstrap job.
This patch set also adds confirming authentication works using  domain-
specific configuration for keystone.

Consolidated change from: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/552976/
Co-Authored-By: Gage Hugo <gagehugo@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I1aeccffc018d0fcefc8e2b15a4ac6b83cb2be8b6
Signed-off-by: Tin Lam <tin@irrational.io>

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-02-23 09:10:46.000000000', 'message': "Fix CI (QoS and running func tests against OVS 2.9 fixes)

This is a combination of 2 commits as we need both to unblock the gate
right now. One will fix the CI due to QoS changes in neutron and the
other will make functional tests running against OVS 2.9 since master is
currently breaking those. Both depend on each other so this is the
reason behind of the squash.

Fix CI broke because of QoS interface and neutron DB interface changes

all_rules = qos_rule.get_rules(context, policy_id)
TypeError: get_rules() takes exactly 3 arguments (2 given)

qos_rule.get_rules() add a arguments (obj_cls) in this commit:
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/6f83466307fb21aee5bb596974644d457ae1fa60#diff-94eb611a8a3b29dbf8cd2aa2466a53b9R34

This code results in a DB commit for each operation (get_object/delete_object/update_object):
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/6f83466307fb21aee5bb596974644d457ae1fa60#diff-7ed10a69652bc41264bbb5ae42eb8867R526
This led to the port's revision_number increase.

Run tempest release job and functional tests against OVS 2.9

This patch makes both the functional tests and tempest release
job to run against OVS 2.9 which is the latest release at the
time that stable/queens is going to be released.

This is also fixing the functional tests that currently run
against OVS master branch and currently breaks those.

Change-Id: I4f3df7b98f7cfcea94367f83f055b3db0450e761
Closes-bug: #1750599
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix CI (QoS and running func tests against OVS 2.9 fixes)

This is a combination of 2 commits as we need both to unblock the gate
right now. One will fix the CI due to QoS changes in neutron and the
other will make functional tests running against OVS 2.9 since master is
currently breaking those. Both depend on each other so this is the
reason behind of the squash.

Fix CI broke because of QoS interface and neutron DB interface changes

all_rules = qos_rule.get_rules(context, policy_id)
TypeError: get_rules() takes exactly 3 arguments (2 given)

qos_rule.get_rules() add a arguments (obj_cls) in this commit:
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/6f83466307fb21aee5bb596974644d457ae1fa60#diff-94eb611a8a3b29dbf8cd2aa2466a53b9R34

This code results in a DB commit for each operation (get_object/delete_object/update_object):
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/6f83466307fb21aee5bb596974644d457ae1fa60#diff-7ed10a69652bc41264bbb5ae42eb8867R526
This led to the port's revision_number increase.

Run tempest release job and functional tests against OVS 2.9

This patch makes both the functional tests and tempest release
job to run against OVS 2.9 which is the latest release at the
time that stable/queens is going to be released.

This is also fixing the functional tests that currently run
against OVS master branch and currently breaks those.

Depends-On: I3ea043758f813f33b4e42eae29b12fadd2e66f7c
Change-Id: I4f3df7b98f7cfcea94367f83f055b3db0450e761
Closes-bug: #1750599
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>

commit_message:
DHCP agent: Handle endpoint with no ipNetworks

If the endpoint has no ipNetworks, treat as deletion.  This happens when
a resync from the mechanism driver overlaps with a port/VM being
deleted.

Before handling this case, we got a traceback like this:

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/bin/calico-dhcp-agent", line 10, in <module>
    sys.exit(main())
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 619, in main
    agent.run()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/osprofiler/profiler.py", line 153, in wrapper
    return f(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 585, in run
    self.etcd.start()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 167, in start
    super(CalicoEtcdWatcher, self).start()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/etcdutils.py", line 323, in start
    self.dispatcher.handle_event(response)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/etcdutils.py", line 73, in handle_event
    self._handle(key_parts, response, self.handler_root, {})
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/etcdutils.py", line 91, in _handle
    handler_node[action](response, **captures)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 278, in on_endpoint_set
    port['network_id'] = self._ensure_net_and_subnets(port)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 325, in _ensure_net_and_subnets
    assert new_subnets
AssertionError

Change-Id: Ic8aa642c8b8c23066bc92e14743b2d0c83ce3459

commit_message:
playbooks: containers-lxc-host: Set correct disk size limit for containers

We need to set the lxc_host_machine_volume_size variable based on the
size of the disk which holds the container images. This avoids spurious
problems in the gates when we run out of disk space inside the
containers.

Change-Id: I3dfea24f6eb9d179174222b907c29126168bbb4e

commit_message:
Simplify SELinux check

The ansible_selinux variable is always populated with a 'status'
property, even if SELinux is not installed or configured. This
patch simplifies the check.

Change-Id: Ifddc385fc292ddb7d6c2758b199401c45de0f0f2
Signed-off-by: Major Hayden <major@mhtx.net>

commit_message:
Update config option for collecting sensor data

This patch updates the notification driver option for collecting sensor
data because [DEFAULT]/notification_driver is deprecated and
'messaging' driver should only be used in cases where there are existing
consumers deployed which do not support the 2.0 message format.

Change-Id: Ia6c55149e5cb12d1201742f7008047e35570b410
(cherry picked from commit 013992bf6668d81e7a5649a313f7475907a644b7)

commit_message:
doc update: better introduction, more links

* avoid having the same intro text in two files (use an include)
* avoid giving the impression that EVPN support is a mere possibility
* update some intro and README.rst text
* link to summit presentation videos

Thanks Ghanshyam for the review. As you said, the reason why this is here is for open discussion and more feedback. If this is merged, there will be documentation in nova with all the accompanying feedback which I think would be useful for the community.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-10-03 14:14:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

The real question in my mind is how often is this preventing a real regression. Belts and suspenders are just extra weight if your pants actually fit.

So I'd like to see evidence of regressions actually getting prevented by this before this goes in the check queue. I think periodically running this and knowning if we're passing patrole is good, but pre-commit gating seems really expensive for something that I don't think we regularly screw up."}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2017-10-03 14:49:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

The softest of -1s because of a small terminology question inline.

> I think periodically running this and knowning if we're passing
> patrole is good, but pre-commit gating seems really expensive for
> something that I don't think we regularly screw up.

I'd tend to agree that "proof of usefulness" would be good here. I'm wondering if there are existing policy fails that we're not aware of because we don't test them?'}, {'account_id': 23186, 'date': '2017-10-05 15:54:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 23186, 'date': '2017-10-05 16:02:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> The real question in my mind is how often is this preventing a real
 > regression. Belts and suspenders are just extra weight if your
 > pants actually fit.
 > 
 > So I'd like to see evidence of regressions actually getting
 > prevented by this before this goes in the check queue. I think
 > periodically running this and knowning if we're passing patrole is
 > good, but pre-commit gating seems really expensive for something
 > that I don't think we regularly screw up.

Thanks for your commentary and review. Patrole was developed downstream before Nova policy in code existed and back when the Nova policy file was incredibly confusing to understand. We use the tool internally to validate custom policy definitions; the heavier the modification to a policy file, the more difficult it is to validate using current tooling.

Thus, the ideal use case for Patrole is to validate custom policy files, though more work needs to be done in that area. However, for any testing framework to function properly -- particularly upstream, where Tempest changes are continuous and where policy in code is now a goal for all projects -- it has to be subjected to symmetric testing, anything that allows us to collect more data to gauge stability.

I do agree that Nova is in a great spot in terms of the stability of its policy implementation. Our use case for trying to get Patrole (as well as Bandit) adoption upstream is to ensure that all services are working securely. To that end, it is reasonable to only run Patrole on a weekly basis (for example) rather than on a per-patch set basis."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:49:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:50:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

We're in Rocky now so this would have to be moved to the rocky directory structure and address reviewer feedback.

There was talk at the rocky PTG about using patrole for testing the RBAC changes coming from Keystone wrt "system scope" but that's probably something that can be done more generally across the integrated gate set of jobs?'}]

subject: Fix Duplicate declaration: Class[Ceph::Keys]
messages:
[{'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-14 02:41:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-14 02:43:29.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to fix-cephkey-duplicate-declaration'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2018-03-14 20:58:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2018-03-14 21:20:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

So this is a problem with the ceph profiles in that you have to define the mons before the client always.  You end up with the wrong defaults if you do it the other way and were to use this code. See https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceph/blob/master/manifests/profile/client.pp#L30'}, {'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-15 00:23:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

If user put OS::TripleO::Services::CephClient before  OS::TripleO::Services::CephOSD.  of CephAll Role in Tripleo roledata . The Deployment wil failed.'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:03:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'll have to check tripleo but I don't think you need the client if you've already defined the mon/osds"}, {'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

see https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/roles/CephAll.yaml#L15
you will find it deploy success or failed be related to ServicesDefaults order in  CephAll role data.'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:32:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yea the issue is with that role, if you have cephmon configured you don't want ceph client configured.  CephClient should be removed from the CephAll role.  The only thing it does is the key set which is already handled by the ceph mon profile."}, {'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:37:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

yea, you are right, I will remove CephClient from CephAll role, and abandon this commit.'}, {'account_id': 24687, 'date': '2018-03-15 14:38:00.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Migrate CLI to cliff

This patch replaces the use of argparse module
by the cliff package. The rationale is that
cliff infrastructure is easier to use and more
functional. Some other OpenStack projects seem
to migrate to cliff already.

Change-Id: Ib2185dad50e64de354222669d2e65f411ddc96a4
Closes-Bug: #1752911

commit_message:
Express forbidden traits in placement API

The spec proposes new syntax and handling for expressing traits that
required to _not_ be present in the results of both GET
/resource_providers and GET /allocation_candidates. The proposed
syntax is designed to minimize a profusion of query parameters. But
it may be too weird, so a syntax using a new parameter is also
proposed.

blueprint placement-forbidden-traits

Change-Id: I4e25c0ae28cf7d9aa75ed75e164ae38d9f4eaa54

commit_message:
Avoid tox-install.sh

Instead of using tox-install.sh, we can install neutron now directly
from pypi - or use the current branch in CI system using tox-siblings.

Create doc/requriements.txt for doc requirements as well.

Update tox.ini for this change

Change-Id: Ia46dd4f27ce529a6742d5724e09ddedba6108785

Change-Id: Ida567c33bb868e1b4a658fbc3cfc16f3e3b0610d
"}, {'created': '2018-03-14 14:19:04.000000000', 'message': "Initialize privsep infrastructure for Calico DHCP agent

Change-Id: Ida567c33bb868e1b4a658fbc3cfc16f3e3b0610d
"}, {'created': '2018-03-14 17:25:12.000000000', 'message': "Initialize privsep infrastructure for Calico DHCP agent

Also handle removal just now of neutron.common.topics.  That now has to
be neutron_lib.agent.topics.

Also enhance the code in our gate hook that emits Calico diags, so that
it doesn't barf itself if something else goes wrong so as to prevent the
whole test from running.

Also remove test_cross_tenant_traffic from the set of Tempest tests that
we run.  This test has been occasionally flaky for a long time, but now
it seems to have increased in failure rate to about 50%.  It has always
been outside the scope that Calico for OpenStack covers, however, so
seems sensible now to just remove it, given that the increased failure
rate is impacting our ability to get good networking-calico changes
merged.

(Technical explanation: This test creates one VM each for two tenants
and tests connectivity between those, subject to appropriate SG config.
The problem for Calico is that both of those VMs get the same IP address
- which Calico does not support because it requires all endpoints to
share an address space.

Specifically what then goes wrong is that one of the VMs does not get
the SSH key metadata that it should; its console log includes:

  ### /etc/init.d/sshd start
  Top of dropbear init script
  Starting dropbear sshd: remove-dropbear-host-keys already run per instance
  WARN: generating key of type ecdsa failed!
  FAIL

I think this is because correct metadata operation with overlapping IPs
requires use of the Neutron metadata agent, and we don't run that in our
DevStack CI setup; instead we run the Nova metadata agent, which is
simpler but only for a single shared address space.

Lack of that key metadata means that a later SSH into that VM fails.

FWIW, other aspects of Calico surprisingly _do_ work up.  (1) The DHCP
agent runs separate dnsmasq instances per tenant, and it's fine for each
of those to hand out the same IP address.  (2) It's ambiguous which VM
the compute host will route to for <the shared fixed IP>, but in this
particular test and setup that doesn't matter because the test maps a
floating IP to the target VM and uses that for SSH, and Felix also
programs a route for <floating IP> to the relevant TAP interface.

So ultimately it's just the SSH key metadata that causes this test to
fail.)

I've had to include _all_ of the above changes in this same commit,
because they are all needed in order for networking-calico CI to pass
again.

Change-Id: Ida567c33bb868e1b4a658fbc3cfc16f3e3b0610d
"}, {'created': '2018-03-14 17:29:02.000000000', 'message': "Initialize privsep infrastructure for Calico DHCP agent

Also handle removal just now of neutron.common.topics.  That now has to
be neutron_lib.agent.topics.

Also enhance the code in our gate hook that emits Calico diags, so that
it doesn't barf itself if something else goes wrong so as to prevent the
whole test from running.

Also remove test_cross_tenant_traffic from the set of Tempest tests that
we run.  This test has been occasionally flaky for a long time, but now
it seems to have increased in failure rate to about 50%.  It has always
been outside the scope that Calico for OpenStack covers, however, so
seems sensible now to just remove it, given that the increased failure
rate is impacting our ability to get good networking-calico changes
merged.

(Technical explanation: This test creates one VM each for two tenants
and tests connectivity between those, subject to appropriate SG config.
The problem for Calico is that both of those VMs get the same IP address
- which Calico does not support because it requires all endpoints to
share an address space.

Specifically what then goes wrong is that one of the VMs does not get
the SSH key metadata that it should; its console log includes:

  ### /etc/init.d/sshd start
  Top of dropbear init script
  Starting dropbear sshd: remove-dropbear-host-keys already run per instance
  WARN: generating key of type ecdsa failed!
  FAIL

I think this is because correct metadata operation with overlapping IPs
requires use of the Neutron metadata agent, and we don't run that in our
DevStack CI setup; instead we run the Nova metadata agent, which is
simpler but only for a single shared address space.

Lack of that key metadata means that a later SSH into that VM fails.

FWIW, other aspects of Calico surprisingly _do_ still work.  (1) The
DHCP agent runs separate dnsmasq instances per tenant, and it's fine for
each of those to hand out the same IP address.  (2) It's ambiguous which
VM the compute host will route to for <the shared fixed IP>, but in this
particular test and setup that doesn't matter because the test maps a
floating IP to the target VM and uses that for SSH, and Felix also
programs a route for <floating IP> to the relevant TAP interface.

So ultimately it's just the SSH key metadata that causes this test to
fail.)

I've had to include _all_ of the above changes in this same commit,
because they are all needed in order for networking-calico CI to pass
again.

Change-Id: Ida567c33bb868e1b4a658fbc3cfc16f3e3b0610d
"}]
commit_message:
Initialize privsep infrastructure for Calico DHCP agent

Also handle removal just now of neutron.common.topics.  That now has to
be neutron_lib.agent.topics.

Also enhance the code in our gate hook that emits Calico diags, so that
it doesn't barf itself if something else goes wrong so as to prevent the
whole test from running.

Also remove test_cross_tenant_traffic from the set of Tempest tests that
we run.  This test has been occasionally flaky for a long time, but now
it seems to have increased in failure rate to about 50%.  It has always
been outside the scope that Calico for OpenStack covers, however, so
seems sensible now to just remove it, given that the increased failure
rate is impacting our ability to get good networking-calico changes
merged.

(Technical explanation: This test creates one VM each for two tenants
and tests connectivity between those, subject to appropriate SG config.
The problem for Calico is that both of those VMs get the same IP address
- which Calico does not support because it requires all endpoints to
share an address space.

Specifically what then goes wrong is that one of the VMs does not get
the SSH key metadata that it should; its console log includes:

  ### /etc/init.d/sshd start
  Top of dropbear init script
  Starting dropbear sshd: remove-dropbear-host-keys already run per instance
  WARN: generating key of type ecdsa failed!
  FAIL

I think this is because correct metadata operation with overlapping IPs
requires use of the Neutron metadata agent, and we don't run that in our
DevStack CI setup; instead we run the Nova metadata agent, which is
simpler but only for a single shared address space.

Lack of that key metadata means that a later SSH into that VM fails.

FWIW, other aspects of Calico surprisingly _do_ still work.  (1) The
DHCP agent runs separate dnsmasq instances per tenant, and it's fine for
each of those to hand out the same IP address.  (2) It's ambiguous which
VM the compute host will route to for <the shared fixed IP>, but in this
particular test and setup that doesn't matter because the test maps a
floating IP to the target VM and uses that for SSH, and Felix also
programs a route for <floating IP> to the relevant TAP interface.

So ultimately it's just the SSH key metadata that causes this test to
fail.)

I've had to include _all_ of the above changes in this same commit,
because they are all needed in order for networking-calico CI to pass
again.

Change-Id: Ida567c33bb868e1b4a658fbc3cfc16f3e3b0610d

commit_message:
Move neutron/horizon to requirements

With recent changes, these need to be moved to requirements to install
correctly.

Note that neutron is still installed from git thanks to tox-siblings in
OpenStack CI.

commit_message:
Add descriptions for config option choices

oslo.config 5.2.0 changed some of the options
(oslo_config.cfg.StrOpt & PortOpt) so that
the choices parameter will now accept a sequence
of tuples, where each tuple is of the form
(choice, description).

If a description is not provided, the sample
config file is generated with
'<No description provided>' next to the choices.

This adds descriptions to the choices.

Change-Id: I7e32ff8e86d2760af49fd088188b94d19ca76e84
Closes-Bug: #1755914

commit_message:
Reduce stestr concurrency to 1 for tempest jobs

The switch from ostestr to stestr introduced in Change-Id
Ie6a275170ec6faf0db3976410660f52078710a54 missed setting concurrency
jobs to 1 for api and scenario tests, leading to intermittent gate
issues.

This patch also fixes coverage test that got broken in the
aforementioned Change-Id.

Change-Id: I077330ad6f0308845d1b5330040be6f92c39580d

commit_message:
Add MasqueradeNetwork parameter until we get spine-leaf support

Until this work is done:
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/topic:containers-routed-spine-leaf

We need the old masquerade_network parameter support on the
containerized undercloud so we can deploy an overcloud with Ironic when
the undercloud is containerized.

commit_message:
Remove cloud-init and disable os-collect-config

A user uses a guest image for the undercloud, cloud-init may be
installed which can also cause other services like os-collect-config to
be running. We should ensure that cloud-init is removed and that the
os-collect-config service is disable to prevent it from interfering with
overcloud deployments.

Change-Id: I58f6fc4b299c8f1f561205ac9a2de75c46467ba8
Closes-Bug: #1754426

commit_message:
Fix gnocchi-upgrade Table <..> already exists errors

Currently we are calling /usr/bin/gnocchi-upgrade
--sacks-number=SACK_NUM from each node where gnocchi-api is part of the
role. gnocchi-upgrade seems to be racy and we sometimes end up with the
following error:

2018-03-14 12:39:39,683 [1] ERROR    oslo_db.sqlalchemy.exc_filters: DBAPIError exception wrapped from (pymysql.err.InternalError) (1050, u"Table 'archive_policy' already exists") [SQL: u'\nCREATE TABLE archive_policy (\n\tname VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL, \n\tback_window INTEGER NOT NULL, \n\tdefinition TEXT NOT NULL, \n\taggregation_methods TEXT NOT NULL, \n\tPRIMARY KEY (name)\n)ENGINE=InnoDB CHARSET=utf8\n\n']
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/site-packages/sqlalchemy/engine/base.py", line 1182, in _execute_context
    context)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/site-packages/sqlalchemy/engine/default.py", line 470, in do_execute
    cursor.execute(statement, parameters)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/cursors.py", line 166, in execute
    result = self._query(query)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/cursors.py", line 322, in _query
    conn.query(q)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/connections.py", line 856, in query
    self._affected_rows = self._read_query_result(unbuffered=unbuffered)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/connections.py", line 1057, in _read_query_result
    result.read()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/connections.py", line 1340, in read
    first_packet = self.connection._read_packet()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/connections.py", line 1014, in _read_packet
    packet.check_error()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/connections.py", line 393, in check_error
    err.raise_mysql_exception(self._data)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pymysql/err.py", line 107, in raise_mysql_exception
    raise errorclass(errno, errval)
InternalError: (1050, u"Table 'archive_policy' already exists")

Let's run it from a the bootstrap node by wrapping it into the
bootstrap_host_exec magic.

Change-Id: I106512eeffff3425608a543f9bc5e6a9508d15e5
Closes-Bug: #1755564

commit_message:
Add retries to apt cache update

Updating the apt cache sometimes fails due to it being
an operation that uses mirrors on the internet. The
task should be retried to reduce the chance of a
transient failure causing the playbook to fail.

Change-Id: I66db37c6a55f9133befd8f9803cab217034547c1
Partial-Bug: #1750656

commit_message:
Add fast_forward_upgrade_tasks for ceilometer services

Adds ffu_tasks for ceilometer - stop services on step 1.
In the docker/ templates services are also disabled.

Lots of changes for ceilo-* since Newton:
  --> openstack-ceilometer-api, -collector and -expirer are
      removed in Pike and no longer in the templates. The disable
      files are re-added by the parent review so these services
      can be retired with ffu_tasks.
  --> The disabled services are set back in environment for Fast
      Forward Upgrade

Change-Id: I1c8ac2285ab222cfb7cb7ff898d222ae6e846567
(cherry picked from commit 92624d6730c47f83d7a97959093a916b5e4e69af)

commit_message:
trivial: Rename reboot kwarg to hard_reboot

This is a trivial refactor of the libvirt driver to make it clear that
the reboot boolean used by _create_domain_and_network only relates to
hard reboots where we fully destroy a domain, unplug VIFs, disconnect
volumes etc before reconnecting volumes, re-plugging VIFs and recreating
the domain.

Soft reboots are handled through a different codepath and so the naming
of this argument could easily confuse anyone reviewing this method and
anything we pass the boolean on to.

Change-Id: I7b3e890b9a95984be71f224345ff59272e0b02c0

commit_message:
use plugin common utils from neutron-lib

The public APIs that are part of neutron.plugins.common.utils were
rehomed into neutron-lib with Iabb155b5d2d0ec6104ebee5dd42cf292bdf3ec61
and will removed in neutron with commit
I1d63cbea463e92e1d2e053f8e1a564ed52cb84f8

This patch consumes the common plugin utils from neutron-lib

NOTE: We will have to rehome create_port and consume it before we can
land the neutron patch.

Change-Id: I78d74718fbfce35a2b51b717fc97274b38e5c583

commit_message:
Move neutron to requirements.txt

Since neutron is now in
global-requirements, we can remove the installation from
tools/tox_install.sh.

Note that neutron is still installed from git thanks to tox-siblings
in OpenStack CI.

Change-Id: I27183e188335bb3002079c0c5743d09e9972bad4

commit_message:
Avoid tox-install.sh

Instead of using tox-install.sh, we can install horizon and neutron
now directly from pypi - or use the current branch in CI system using
tox-siblings.

Update tox.ini for this change and add neutron to requirements file.

Change-Id: Iac4eceb6201724b6e9c3ee967139a4c10ee62f9b

commit_message:
Disallow TLS v1.0 from HAProxy

This forces HAProxy to only accept newer versions of TLS, which allows
us to meet FedRAMP requirements.

Change-Id: I14f4de3875a743ee5328b13668790b26cefd8439
Related-Bug: #1754368

commit_message:
Add retries to apt cache update

Updating the apt cache sometimes fails due to it being
an operation that uses mirrors on the internet. The
task should be retried to reduce the chance of a
transient failure causing the playbook to fail.

Change-Id: Icec853745b4aaa9f8745ec5cb42d85ccc606bac0
Partial-Bug: #1750656

commit_message:
Disallow TLS v1.0 from HAProxy

This forces HAProxy to only accept newer versions of TLS, which allows
us to meet FedRAMP requirements.

Change-Id: I14f4de3875a743ee5328b13668790b26cefd8439
Related-Bug: #1754368
(cherry picked from commit ebde918b0f0cea8715a30f57ca7c2683dd477c50)

adding this info to our logs.

Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Create lockfiles directory in CNI Dockerfile

This commit adds creating a directory for lockfiles in the CNI Docker
image. As in oslo.concurrency `lock_path` option defaults to
`OSLO_LOCK_PATH` environment variable, this variable is also set to
point to that directory.

Change-Id: Ia69c75c34a8da4281414395805f4927de1e91a39
Closes-Bug: 1754636

commit_message:
Remove prefix of AuditTemplate object

Sometimes there are conflicts with creating audits
at the same time[1]. This fix is aimed to reduce
length of audittemplate object to give audit name
more space for time suffix.

[1]: http://logs.openstack.org/90/551790/24/check/watcher-tempest-zuulv3/a0143d5/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-03-15_09_05_31_272087

The purpose of this function is:
1, if the container has an abnormal situation, such as error status, but you still want to continue to use the container, retain all its information (network, etc.), you can use this feature;
2, the container does not actually exist, but still retains database records, network resources, etc., you can use this function to try to restore the container

commit_message:
zun rebuild on local node

Provide reconstruction function, if the container A is damaged,
users can use this function to recreate a container B.
The container B and A use the same resources, such as network, CPU, etc.

Change-Id: I3c12d6cb1501d7c382c9518e1d2544d80ea610f6
Implements:blueprint zun-rebuild-on-local-node

commit_message:
libvirt: Skip VNIC_TYPE_DIRECT port vif-plugged events during a hard reboot

As with VIF_TYPE_BRIDGE ports we should not rely on Neutron sending
vif-plugged events for VNIC_TYPE_DIRECT ports during a hard reboot.

Change-Id: If209f77cff2de00f694b01b2507c633ec3882c82

commit_message:
Refine waiting for vif plug events during _hard_reboot

In change Ib0cf5d55750f13d0499a570f14024dca551ed4d4, we stopped waiting
for vif plug events during hard reboot and start, because the behavior
of neutron plug events depended on the vif type and we couldn't rely on
the stale network info cache.

This refines the logic not to wait for vif plug events only for the
bridge vif type, instead of for all types. We also add a flag to
_create_domain_and_network to indicate that we're in the middle of a
reboot and to expect to wait for plug events for all vif types except
the bridge vif type, regardless of the vif's 'active' status.

We only query network_info from neutron at the beginning of a reboot,
before we've unplugged anything, so the majority of the time, the vifs
will be active=True. The current logic in get_neutron_events will only
expect events for vifs with 'active' status False. This adds a way to
override that if we know we've already unplugged vifs as part of a
reboot.

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

NOTE(lyarwood): Ica323b87fa85a454fca9d46ada3677f18fe50022 and
I13de970c3beed29311d43991115a0c6d28ac14e0 are the source of the above
conflicts in driver.py. The first removed encryptor attach logic from
_create_domain_and_network in Queens while the second altered the
signature of _create_domain_and_network in Queens, removing reboot that
is then reintroduced with this change.

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py
        nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

NOTE(lyarwood): As with the stable/ocata version of
Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986 these conflicts are caused by
_create_domain_and_network using an additional disk_info argument prior
to Pike, this is now documented and provided in the tests.

Related-Bug: #1744361

Change-Id: Ib08afad3822f2ca95cfeea18d7f4fc4cb407b4d6
(cherry picked from commit aaf37a26d6caa124f0cc6c3fe21bfdf58ccb8517)
(cherry picked from commit 5a10047f9dd4383f6ec9046d392f26c93f8420d4)
(cherry picked from commit e06ad602f3ef98c505e49078dd225dde2a79e2a1)

I see. This is a good point. Then, how about doing this "df /workdir_path/docker". Does it display the disk size properly in your scenario? If yes, we can introduce a new config, such as CONF.docker.data_root. The default value should be "/var/lib/docker" which is the default root directory of persistent Docker state. As a result, you can set this config as "/workdir_path/docker" in your case.

Let me fix that for you properly...'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2018-03-14 19:29:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

https://review.openstack.org/553017 should fix it'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2018-03-14 21:38:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> Let me fix that for you properly...

The changes you propose will prevent a project from depending on the master branch of a project. It happens that many networking-* or neutron-* project are co-developed with neutron and sometimes will depend  on features that are not in a released version of neutron. Your changes would, unless I misunderstood, prevent this workflow.

Perhaps the current practice has drawbacks and needs to be revisited, although it seems to me quite legitimate to expect that to be possible in the Neutron stadium.

Either way, I think that it would be preferable to first discuss and agree on a solution that will work for everyone, rather than rush on this path.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2018-03-14 21:40:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thomas, we install *exactly* the same way as before from git.

See http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2018-March/128311.html - let's discuss there."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2018-03-14 22:17:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I have similar questions. I sent a mail to the dev list. http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2018-March/128318.html'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2018-03-15 09:32:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2018-03-15 09:33:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

if pulling from git is till supported, then no need to revert
more discussion as a follow up, on openstack-dev'}]

Revert "Add neutron and horizon to global requirements"

This commit causes issues in repo using a tools/tox_install.sh to install neutron or horizon from git.

2018-03-14 11:01:42.726827 | ubuntu-xenial | Obtaining file:///home/zuul/src/git.openstack.org/openstack/networking-bgpvpn/.tmp/tmp.WpFRUuEq20/openstack/neutron
2018-03-14 11:01:42.727140 | ubuntu-xenial | Could not satisfy constraints for 'neutron': installation from path or url cannot be constrained to a version
2018-03-14 11:01:42.727181 | ubuntu-xenial |

I suggest reverting and doing more testing until everyting is ready to avoid breaking CI.

This reverts commit 35653e8c5044bff1059ddddf50a82b6065176eea.

commit_message:
Update minimum version of docker in unit tests

python docker version in u-c is bumped to 3.1.1 in [1].
Till 2.7.0 if MINIMUM_DOCKER_API_VERSION it just reported
warning but since 3.0.0 it reports Error, see [2]. This
patch bumps the expected version to 1.21 which is same
docker version used in magnum and supported by current
python docker.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/551428/
[2] https://github.com/docker/docker-py/commit/df8422d0791d7d03cd3e1efe37a9c72f242f1f78

Change-Id: Id93c5f70504c7d686dbd1b3d9bdfc1ef657d9287

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-03-14 21:46:52.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure leader settings on charm upgrade

Currently bootstrapping is gated by is_leader_bootstrapped which
checks a handful of leader settings. When upgrading from older
versions of the charm, these settings are missing leading to an
attempt to bootstrap an already bootstrapped cluster.

This change makes sure the leader settings is_leader_bootstrapped is
checking for are all set by the leader on upgrade-charm.

Closes-Bug: #1755507

Change-Id: I172f10221b9447ca3e0c5403feaa49acccfa9e42
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure leader settings on charm upgrade

Currently bootstrapping is gated by is_leader_bootstrapped which
checks a handful of leader settings. When upgrading from older
versions of the charm, these settings are missing leading to an
attempt to bootstrap an already bootstrapped cluster.

This change makes sure the leader settings is_leader_bootstrapped is
checking for are all set by the leader on upgrade-charm.

Closes-Bug: #1755507

Change-Id: I172f10221b9447ca3e0c5403feaa49acccfa9e42

commit_message:
Refactor some common code between overcloud_upgrade and update

Adds a new run_update_ansible_action function in utils to be used by
the upgrade and update to avoid repetition. The package_update action is
passed into the utils function to avoid circular dependency.

Change-Id: Idbe0a98fa8f2e8dfe220796c02593a805942b0da

commit_message:
Remove /lib/udev in $PATH for nova-compute

Add /lib/udev environment variable[1] is to solve the scsi_id access
problems, but the patch[2][3] pointed out the absolute path scsi_id,
we can not add /lib/udev environment variables in the system for
nova-compute. So we can remove /lib/udev in $PATH for nova-compute.

[1]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/291285/
[2]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/277224/
[3]https://github.com/openstack/os-brick/blob/master/os_brick/initiator/linuxscsi.py#L147

Change-Id: I5326edf8fff5745ef119c0c3decd6f4c51e8bd5d
Closes-Bug: #1742340
(cherry picked from commit 097b4da85d81a2ce892ffbc208dc5710b519441c)

commit_message:
Remove the errored steps after they all responded

Removing steps during the initial loop could cause some issues and race
conditions.

This change makes it so the steps are filtered out after they all responded.
Since it waits for the global resolve to moves on, this change should not
make anything slower.

Closes-bug: #1702728
Change-Id: Iabfdd3445117b898251782969c3d915b802f440e
(cherry picked from commit e742950da140fa12d078b495a2b8da64c64bd142)

commit_message:
Tabs in launch server wizard not depending on OPENSTACK_NOVA_EXTENSIONS_BLACKLIST

OPENSTACK_NOVA_EXTENSIONS_BLACKLIST is used to disable specific extension.
In the launch instance wizard, by example the Server Group tab should be hidden
when the extension "ServerGroups" is blacklisted but it isn't.

It could be interesting to make these tabs dependent of the supported extensions.

Change-Id: I15ea0f1010e3889c217c63e98f1752a4c1ad9ceb
Closes-Bug: #1745367
(cherry picked from commit c7bc9242b9fa416f510023f50898de1d963909c9)

commit_message:
Avoid tox-install.sh

Instead of using tox-install.sh, we can install horizon and neutron
now directly from pypi - or use the current branch in CI system using
tox-siblings.

commit_message:
Use oslo.context from_dict unmodified

With the change to oslo.context in the depends-on, we no longer need
to maintain an override for the from_dict function.  We only need
to provide a list of additional keys in the appropriate class member.

This will work with oslo.context 2.19.2 and above, which is now the
minimum version in global-requirements.

Depends-On: Ib143f8a5c129dbf6711800c4d87c8830a8aa3365

Change-Id: If09a3b22465b196baa34edc00c7472f5feed4ba5

[{'created': '2017-11-13 13:40:46.000000000', 'message': "neutron: Call destroy-patch-ports before starting ovs-agent

The script called destroy-patch-ports will break connection between the
integration bridge and provider bridges configured in Neutron config
files. See https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1490281 for more
details about the reason.

With systemd, we have control over dependencies between services,
therefore we can tell that destroy-patch-ports service must be run
before neutron-openvswitch-agent. But we do not have this ability using
docker. That's why this patch simply calls the script before each start
of the agent. To avoid unnecessary breakage of patch ports, the script
was enhanced to check a canary flow on integration bridge and in case
the flow is there, it will not delete the patch ports. Presence of
canary flow on integration bridge means that bridge has been already
configured. It also implies provider bridges are configured too and thus
they can't cause the ARP storm as described in Red Hat Bugzilla 1490281.

NOTE: This patch requires the packaging side to be merged first:
      https://review.rdoproject.org/r/#/c/10480/

Closes-bug: #1731924

commit_message:
neutron: Call destroy-patch-ports before starting ovs-agent

The script called destroy-patch-ports will break connection between the
integration bridge and provider bridges configured in Neutron config
files. See https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1490281 for more
details about the reason.

With systemd, we have control over dependencies between services,
therefore we can tell that destroy-patch-ports service must be run
before neutron-openvswitch-agent. But we do not have this ability using
docker. That's why this patch simply calls the script before each start
of the agent. To avoid unnecessary breakage of patch ports, the script
was enhanced to check a canary flow on integration bridge and in case
the flow is there, it will not delete the patch ports. Presence of
canary flow on integration bridge means that bridge has been already
configured. It also implies provider bridges are configured too and thus
they can't cause the ARP storm as described in Red Hat Bugzilla 1490281.

NOTE: This patch requires the packaging side to be merged first:
      https://review.rdoproject.org/r/#/c/10480/

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>

Closes-bug: #1731924

Change-Id: I005af23b1815c904ef63676553df9b14b7edfbfc

Upon K8S service creation the LBaaS handler creates all LB resources
at neutron (LB,Listener,Pool,etc) and store them at K8S resource
 using annotation.
When K8S service is deleted, the LBaaS handler retrieves LB
resources details from annotation and release them at neutron.

This patch handles the case in which K8S service resource was deleted before
LBaaS stored openstack resource details.

commit_message:
Services: Rollback openstack resources in case of annotation failure

Upon K8S service creation the LBaaS handler creates all LB resources
at neutron (LB,Listener,Pool,etc) and store them at K8S resource
 using annotation.
When K8S service is deleted, the LBaaS handler retrieves LB
resources details from annotation and release them at neutron.

This patch handles the case in which K8S service resource was deleted
before LBaaS handler stored openstack resource details.

Closes-Bug: 1748890

Change-Id: Iea806d32c99cd3cf51a832b576ff4054fc522bd3

commit_message:
Services: Gracefully ignore exposed UDP ports

Since LBaaSv2 doesn't support UDP load balancing,
Kuryr should ignore exposed UDP ports in K8S service.
This patch updates Kuryr to gracefully ignore UDP exposed
ports and updates the documentation with this info.

Closes-Bug: 1736060

Change-Id: I03f6d95a2d855cbd8954018c930e283a46763655

commit_message:
Blacklist Sphinx 1.6.7

Certain documentation jobs are failing with Sphinx 1.6.7 because
Sphinx ignores modules with only __init__.py files, but doesn't
actually account for sub-directories. Version 1.6.5 doesn't seem
to have this behavior.

Change-Id: I84310799cbbca90f8cb8b3667cddadd8a4202d06

commit_message:
Rearrange cell mapping tasks

Existing instances can be mapped to a newly created cell immediately
after the cell is created and by the same conductor host that created
the cell.

After a new compute host is built, it will need to mapped to a cell
through the 'discover_hosts' command of nova-manage. This command will
still need to be run against a host that has direct database access, but
the command is able to handle mapping of all compute hosts that do not
currently belong to the cell so it only needs to be run once per play.

There can be a short delay in the time between a compute service
starting and becoming available to be discovered and mapped but, for
most deployments, compute host discovery will be handled automatically
as a periodic task.

Conflicts:
>------tasks/main.yml

Change-Id: I4f7328e1aff79eb94f278999b97fbad8f44c6a3e
Closes-Bug: 1749037
Related-Bug: 1729661
Related-Bug: 1752540
(cherry picked from commit 6321cf90304023c20dc6abb87e2fa20107b7051d)

We run full tempest in featureset020, which is a bit resource

commit_message:
Explicitly set tempest workers for full tempest featureset

We run full tempest in featureset020, which is a bit resource
intensive for CI. If we use the dynamic approach of setting
concurrency to half the CPUs, we end up with random failures.

This patch instead changes the concurrency to 2 only for this
featureset.

Change-Id: I6653d6b4851deb5fb64ffc3734a5a4556b51c57a
Closes-Bug: #1755834

commit_message:
ifcfg: don't restart ovs if --no-activate is specified

When --no-activate is specified, there is a chance that
openvswitch service will still be restarted if dpdk port
configuration file is changed. This adds a condition to
check activate and restart openvswitch only if activate
is true.

Change-Id: Ia5a6d04eb26cc3a6e10caacb8256d6e2d183239e
Closes-Bug: #1751955
(cherry picked from commit 9e3436262d14fd90c19c271ae66474ea5eef4ec1)

This adds a required, mutually exclusive argument group for

commit_message:
Add --roles and --nodes params to overcloud upgrade run cli

This adds a required, mutually exclusive argument group for
--roles and --nodes. --roles replaces the existing --role.

This shifts the semantics of upgrading 'one at a time' (compute)
vs 'all together' (controller) to the operator. You can either
specify roles or nodes but not both. Using nodes for contollers
is not supported but we can only warn.

  openstack overcloud upgrade run --roles Controller
  openstack overcloud upgrade run --nodes overcloud-compute-0 overcloud-compute-1
  #for the really ambitious
  openstack overcloud upgrade run --roles Controller Networker

Change-Id: I0418883557113b5a67cfeaf181614dc5fe32ca94
(cherry picked from commit b84e4e13d5bc058cd1f6eab3ca962ee6ccd731a0)

commit_message:
Modify OVB stack and resource identifiers to match te-broker

The ovb-manage-stack role creates OVB stacks in a similar way
to te-broker. However the patterns of naming the stacks and the
related resources were different. This review changes the naming
pattern of the ovb-manage-stack role to match that used with
te-broker to allow for a more uniform mangement of stacks
across tenants and host clouds.

Change-Id: I5c764b9eb9d49e75998d8fe39f41ac90ec00df73

subject: WIP:Specification for using cache as a resource using cache allocation support with resource director technology and resource monitoring daemon.
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7, 'name': 'Jay Pipes', 'email': 'jaypipes@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaypipes'}, {'_account_id': 1063, 'name': 'Ed Leafe', 'email': 'ed@leafe.com', 'username': 'ed-leafe'}, {'_account_id': 5754, 'name': 'Alex Xu', 'email': 'hejie.xu@intel.com', 'username': 'xuhj'}, {'_account_id': 8768, 'name': 'Chris Friesen', 'email': 'chris.friesen@windriver.com', 'username': 'cbf123'}, {'_account_id': 11347, 'name': 'Rui Zang', 'email': 'rui.zang@yandex.com', 'username': 'rzang'}, {'_account_id': 11564, 'name': 'Chris Dent', 'email': 'cdent@anticdent.org', 'username': 'chdent'}, {'_account_id': 11604, 'name': 'sean mooney', 'email': 'smooney@redhat.com', 'username': 'sean-k-mooney'}, {'_account_id': 12175, 'name': 'Eli Qiao', 'email': 'qiaoliyong@gmail.com', 'username': 'Eli'}, {'_account_id': 12597, 'name': 'Lin Yang', 'email': 'lin.a.yang@intel.com', 'username': 'lin.yang'}, {'_account_id': 14091, 'name': 'Yih Leong Sun', 'email': 'yihleong@gmail.com', 'username': 'yihleongsun'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 20207, 'date': '2017-09-11 20:24:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-09-11 23:02:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-docs-ubuntu-xenial http://docs-draft.openstack.org/75/502575/1/check/gate-nova-specs-docs-ubuntu-xenial/ba94a1f//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 4m 37s
- gate-nova-specs-pep8-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/75/502575/1/check/gate-nova-specs-pep8-ubuntu-xenial/a46aaa8/ : SUCCESS in 2m 55s
- gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/75/502575/1/check/gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial/f2e6c00/ : SUCCESS in 3m 28s'}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2017-10-03 18:37:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(9 comments)

I think that ultimately the compute nodes should report "MB of cache available" and "granularity of cache allocation" to placement on a per-numa-node basis.

Initially though placement might only care about per-compute-node numbers, while the NUMATopologyFilter would handle the more fine-grained checks as to whether or not a given NUMA node has sufficient cache available to satisfy the request.'}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2017-10-03 20:26:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Just a note that it might make more sense to report "number of cacheways" and "size of cacheway in KB" or something like that....whatever works best with placement.

But I'd expect the end-user to have a desired amount of cache in MB for their particular application code.'}, {'account_id': 1063, 'date': '2017-10-03 21:40:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I'm not clear why this needs special handling, and can't be successfully modeled using a ResourceClass. Placement would be able to run queries that only return hosts with this particular cache feature, and it would then be up to a scheduler filter and/or weigher to apply the logic for determining the best fit."}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2017-10-04 15:28:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ed...it's sort of akin to CPU pinning in that (where the host processor supports this feature) there are a specific number of cacheways that can be allocated on each host NUMA node, and when flavor/image requests a certain amount of cache that gets mapped to *specific* bits in a bitmask.  (And just to make it interesting these bits have to be contiguous.)

So yes, it would be possible to model it the same way we do CPU pinning in NUMATopologyFilter, but I think the intent was to start doing things the "new" way with placement.

There's also the design question of whether the nova developers are okay with nova calling out to the RMD for cache operations.

Ultimately I'm in favour of the concept, but I think there are some issues to be worked out first.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2018-03-12 13:42:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-03-14 13:59:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

I'm close to a -2 on this. Eli and Sunku, for me to be positive on this blueprint you will need to do the following:

1) demonstrate that this kind of low-level optimization is not best integrated into libvirt/QEMU first -- just like the many, many NUMA/pinning/huge page features that we've already integrated into Nova via libvirt/QEMU functionality

2) demonstrate that RDT/CAT technology leads to a significant real-time guarantee or performance improvement *over the already-existing NUMA node/core pinning features* that we already support.

Thanks,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-03-14 14:18:17.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

This spec is targeted at Pike, we're now in Rocky, so this is obviously abandoned."}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2018-03-14 15:49:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 20207, 'date': '2018-03-15 00:59:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

@Jay Pipes, The reference to white paper in the reference secion covers the questions on the value. As an example, NFV use cases require guaranteed cache quality of service with complicated overlapping/isolated cache schema. The performance vary from upto 80% in degradation (throughput) with wrong cache associations to over 80% improvement in latency with right cache associations. The complexity of required cache schema is currently better addressed by RMD while proving it difficult for libvirts design. Simple static cache pinning doesnt necessarily help all applications. 
-Sunku'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2018-03-15 02:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2018-03-15 03:09:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2018-03-15 03:13:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Some suggestions to simplify the design document. Sunku, happy to work with you on it offline so you can submit a Rocky release design.'}]

[{'created': '2018-03-13 21:01:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fix api-ref response code title levels

Using the wrong character resulted in the wrong title level
being used for the response codes, which in turn caused the
"detail" show/hide toggle to not be able to hide all of the
per-endpoint details. This corrects these to be at the correct
level.

Also ran into issues after changing them where sphinx was not
happy with the random title levels. This appears to be due to
the order processed and whether not earlier included files had
all subsequent levels. Adding an additional title in our first
included file resolved that problem.

Change-Id: I19405778980310f2d6d06eb7b23102f74a3d6e03
Closes-bug: #1755566
'}]
commit_message:
Fix api-ref response code title levels

Using the wrong character resulted in the wrong title level
being used for the response codes, which in turn caused the
"detail" show/hide toggle to not be able to hide all of the
per-endpoint details. This corrects these to be at the correct
level.

Also ran into issues after changing them where sphinx was not
happy with the random title levels. This appears to be due to
the order processed and whether not earlier included files had
all subsequent levels. Adding an additional title in our first
included file resolved that problem.

Change-Id: I19405778980310f2d6d06eb7b23102f74a3d6e03
Closes-bug: #1755566

commit_message:
py3: port cli form_signature and unit tests

This patch ports the form_signature cli `swift-form-signature`
and it's corrisponding tests to py3.

In essence in Py3 the HMAC function expects binary strings.

Change-Id: I5dded4ceb80f0cc595403775e8f9c17873e1e37b

commit_message:
Avoid tox-install.sh

Instead of using tox-install.sh, we can install horizon and neutron
now directly from pypi - or use the current branch in CI system using
tox-siblings.

Update tox.ini for this change and add horizon to requirements file.

Change-Id: I63a753d78eef2938e74b29802f81369607db4d1d

commit_message:
Fix installing Horizon from src for tox env

After this patch [1] is merged into openstack/requirements, we cannot
use pip to install Horizion from src with the upper-constraints. We're
going to rely on the requirements of Horizion instead, and another run
of pip install will also go with the upper-contraints after Horizon is
installed.

Tox env deps is also updated to follow the changes introduced by another
patch [2], but tox_install.sh is still kept for installing Horizion.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/550475/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/508061/

Change-Id: I41042e5cedffe5793ef7af3ee5e3bf3d0577e87b
Signed-off-by: Zhao Chao <zhaochao1984@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Fix tests using O_TMPFILE

Unit tests using O_TMPFILE only rely on the kernel version to check
for the feature. This is wrong, as some filesystem, like tmpfs, doesn't
support O_TMPFILE.

So, instead of checking kernel version, this patch actually attempts to
open a file using O_TMPFILE and see if that's supported. If not, then
the test is skipped.

Change-Id: I5d652f1634b1ef940838573cfdd799ea17b8b572

Clean out config deprecation information

Nova settings were deprecated, then removed in change
Ic112a68101c0dcb14da0db06c62ae190474a37d9. Some legacy

to the old config setting that should now be removed.

commit_message:
Set rgw_keystone_revocation_interval to 0 for ceph-ansible

Ceph RGW defaults to checking every 600 seconds for a revocation.
This is only useful for PKI tokens. PKI is not enabled.
This check needs to be disabled.

Change-Id: I9d87ff5226ab55df05e68f6639e6679fb0566484
Closes-Bug: #1748137
(cherry picked from commit 05b8f5ef67b98d9fc284835c9411c40ead8cf095)

commit_message:
Return nested parameters for resource group.

This refactors the building of schema from parameter validation to use a
new method (which doesn't keep stacks in memory), and use that new
method for providing proper schema for resource group when the size is
0.

Change-Id: Id3020e8f3fd94e2cef413d5eb9de9d1cd16ddeaa
Closes-Bug: #1751074
Closes-Bug: #1626025
(cherry picked from commit 9f73a232d766a3d7f3baac149c587db99b92aa81)

commit_message:
Subnet segment_id writable extension

To enable the possibility to migrate a non-routed network to a
routed network allow updating the segment_id of a subnet.

Partial-Bug: #1692490

The default attach_mode for volume attachments is "rw", as can
be seen from looking at the VolumeAttachment.finish_attach method
and VolumeManager.attachment_update method. The REST API itself
does not set or return a default attach_mode, it's all set in the

connector.

Change-Id: I1e41e93bd534d830311a653eb16fef89a2d8431a
'}]
commit_message:
Fix API reference attach_mode parameter default for attachments API

The default attach_mode for volume attachments is "rw", as can
be seen from looking at the VolumeAttachment.finish_attach method
and VolumeManager.attachment_update method. The REST API itself
does not set or return a default attach_mode, it's all set in the
data model when the attachment is 'completed' by assigning a host
connector.

Change-Id: I1e41e93bd534d830311a653eb16fef89a2d8431a

commit_message:
Remove duplicate declaration of rpc_response_timeout

RPC client option "rpc_response_timeout" is registered as
a part of oslo_messaging config [1]. The existing option in
mistral's config just duplecates it, which leads to two
equal options in the generated sample config.

To prevent this we can remove the related registration in
mistral without hesitation.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/oslo_messaging/rpc/client.py#L41-L45

Change-Id: Ie1856ab6308a4d53584a5829251078961e886f05

commit_message:
Set rgw_keystone_revocation_interval to 0 for ceph::rgw::keystone

Ceph RGW defaults to checking every 600 seconds for a revocation.
This is only useful for PKI tokens. PKI is not enabled. This check
needs to be disabled.

Closes-Bug: #1748137
Change-Id: I2487ce8e5cb5d3dc0d7fb8e547a4abe0e086ff4b
(cherry picked from commit 9aa495d8abdd96d47533c37a0009cfe74533f276)

commit_message:
Rearrange cell mapping tasks

Existing instances can be mapped to a newly created cell immediately
after the cell is created and by the same conductor host that created
the cell.

After a new compute host is built, it will need to mapped to a cell
through the 'discover_hosts' command of nova-manage. This command will
still need to be run against a host that has direct database access, but
the command is able to handle mapping of all compute hosts that do not
currently belong to the cell so it only needs to be run once per play.

There can be a short delay in the time between a compute service
starting and becoming available to be discovered and mapped but, for
most deployments, compute host discovery will be handled automatically
as a periodic task.

Conflicts:
>------tasks/main.yml

Change-Id: I4f7328e1aff79eb94f278999b97fbad8f44c6a3e
Closes-Bug: 1749037
Related-Bug: 1729661
Related-Bug: 1752540
(cherry picked from commit 6321cf90304023c20dc6abb87e2fa20107b7051d)

The object reconstructor has a handoffs-only mode that is very useful
when a cluster requires rapid rebalancing, like when disks are nearing

commit_message:
Add handoffs-only mode to DB replicators.

The object reconstructor has a handoffs-only mode that is very useful
when a cluster requires rapid rebalancing, like when disks are nearing
fullness. This mode's goal is to remove handoff partitions from disks
without spending effort on primary partitions. The object replicator
has a similar mode, though it varies in some details.

This commit adds a handoffs-only mode to the account and container
replicators.

Change-Id: I588b151ee65ae49d204bd6bf58555504c15edf9f
Closes-Bug: 1668399

commit_message:
novajoin: Optionally configure kerberos

This enables the puppet module to optionally create a minimal kerberos
configuration. This is specially useful when running novajoin inside a
container, since when running with SELinux enabled, we sometimes cannot
load the the kerberos configuration from the host due to some includes
pointing to /var/lib.

Change-Id: I554125fd6b48e620370f9e3a6061bbdc1d55b0ae

commit_message:
Refine waiting for vif plug events during _hard_reboot

In change Ib0cf5d55750f13d0499a570f14024dca551ed4d4, we stopped waiting
for vif plug events during hard reboot and start, because the behavior
of neutron plug events depended on the vif type and we couldn't rely on
the stale network info cache.

This refines the logic not to wait for vif plug events only for the
bridge vif type, instead of for all types. We also add a flag to
_create_domain_and_network to indicate that we're in the middle of a
reboot and to expect to wait for plug events for all vif types except
the bridge vif type, regardless of the vif's 'active' status.

We only query network_info from neutron at the beginning of a reboot,
before we've unplugged anything, so the majority of the time, the vifs
will be active=True. The current logic in get_neutron_events will only
expect events for vifs with 'active' status False. This adds a way to
override that if we know we've already unplugged vifs as part of a
reboot.

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

NOTE(lyarwood): Ica323b87fa85a454fca9d46ada3677f18fe50022 and
I13de970c3beed29311d43991115a0c6d28ac14e0 are the source of the above
conflicts in driver.py. The first removed encryptor attach logic from
_create_domain_and_network in Queens while the second altered the
signature of _create_domain_and_network in Queens, removing reboot that
is then reintroduced with this change.

Related-Bug: #1744361

Change-Id: Ib08afad3822f2ca95cfeea18d7f4fc4cb407b4d6
(cherry picked from commit aaf37a26d6caa124f0cc6c3fe21bfdf58ccb8517)
(cherry picked from commit 5a10047f9dd4383f6ec9046d392f26c93f8420d4)

commit_message:
Refine waiting for vif plug events during _hard_reboot

In change Ib0cf5d55750f13d0499a570f14024dca551ed4d4, we stopped waiting
for vif plug events during hard reboot and start, because the behavior
of neutron plug events depended on the vif type and we couldn't rely on
the stale network info cache.

This refines the logic not to wait for vif plug events only for the
bridge vif type, instead of for all types. We also add a flag to
_create_domain_and_network to indicate that we're in the middle of a
reboot and to expect to wait for plug events for all vif types except
the bridge vif type, regardless of the vif's 'active' status.

We only query network_info from neutron at the beginning of a reboot,
before we've unplugged anything, so the majority of the time, the vifs
will be active=True. The current logic in get_neutron_events will only
expect events for vifs with 'active' status False. This adds a way to
override that if we know we've already unplugged vifs as part of a
reboot.

Related-Bug: #1744361

Change-Id: Ib08afad3822f2ca95cfeea18d7f4fc4cb407b4d6

commit_message:
Don't validate local_link_connection when port has client-id

Infiniband ports do not require the local_link_connection field to be
populated as the network topology is discoverable by the Infiniband
Subnet Manager.

This change removes the requirement for local_link_connection for
Infiniband ports. Infiniband ports have a client-id in their extra
field.

Closes-Bug: #1753222
Change-Id: I2bfac4ccaf825bd9aa8ea0d2b447fcd7767acbc5

commit_message:
Add a warning to user: Unable to remove availability zone from host aggregate

Because the nova API does not allow to set aggregates an empty
availability_zone which has availability_zone at first.
Add a warning to notice users to reduce confusion

Change-Id: I5864c58751ec5f182f30feb302a95923948ad2ad
Closes-Bug: #1644051

commit_message:
Ensure mtu is set correctly on ctlplane

We were not passing the MTU when we create the ctlplane network so if
the local_mtu is less than 1500, 1500 is used by the ctlplane network in
neutron.

Change-Id: Ic7a4c5a62ff49b2f8964dd58bf5c97d9781c4ce1
Related-Bug: #1754036

commit_message:
Avoid conflicting delegation with authorized_keys

When delegating with the authorized_key module, writes of multiple keys
against the same host's file can occur at the same time, leading to
missing keys.[0]

To avoid conflicting delegation between hosts, the registered
'keystone_pubkey' fact now contains a list of SSH keys of all hosts the
current batch of the play, rather than only the key of the current host.
The first host within each batch will handle distribution of that
batch's keys to all hosts within the play.

[0] https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/29693

Change-Id: I386e84eba46aa164db22618b7a6ac53b86eeeaf0
(cherry picked from commit 97428cb0a1d66a8d7c266d7807b150b09bac2750)

commit_message:
Explicitly specify if to run validation in undercloud

Set pingtest and tempest to explicit values for undercloud only
job so that we can enable validation roles for undercloud and
to run only required validation - either tempest, or pingtest.

Change-Id: I8f1d350e5e74ea77191255b7b086404b1db8ff00

commit_message:
Include active nodes when matching nodes by profile

When matching nodes by profile, consider nodes in either the 'active'
or 'available' provisioning states. Unless nodes in the 'active' state
are included, the derived parameters workflow fails on stack updates.

Co-Authored-By: Alan Bishop <abishop@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I575d0c358b9efccdefddb26258839def43ebeafd
Closes-Bug: #1752893

commit_message:
docker-puppet.py: don't pull if image exists

This updates the pull function here so that it matches
how paunch also handle's images, only pulling them if
the existing image doesn't already exist on the host.

Change-Id: I90ea41ccdfdb0b9206a63901554d002a5ec0fd3a

commit_message:
Fix bootstrap NAT

Docker will switch the FORWARD filter to DROP if it sets the ip_forward
to 1. Previously we were doing this in a post configuration element
rather than in the puppet run itself. This change moves the ip_forward=1
to puppet so it runs prior to docker being installed. Additionally we
are ensuring that the full set of network rules are being added to the
FORWARD filter because previously we were only setting half of them.
This would allow us to actually not have to use ACCEPT as the default
for the FORWARD filter but this would require additional testing.

Conflicts:
	elements/puppet-stack-config/puppet-stack-config.yaml.template
	elements/undercloud-install/os-refresh-config/post-configure.d/98-undercloud-setup

Change-Id: Ieae6a74f7269bd64606fd80a2a08b2058c24d2c5
Closes-Bug: #1750194
Closes-Bug: #1750874
(cherry picked from commit bfb758b5e792c83e5cde9847bcad424fcfaf071d)
(cherry picked from commit 50217d7a93dce7fdc17c0dfbb04260f86fd3ac7d)

commit_message:
Add flag to enable SELinux in docker profile

SELinux for docker is disabled by default; this commit adds an option
selinux_enabled that will add it if set to true.

Change-Id: I883e64c1b69b24c75441fc3a628942fb1d90d448

commit_message:
Do not attempt install kernel when chrooted

When building images from a container/chroot, do not
attempt to install kernels.
Use the shared via the common defaults chrooted param
to control that behavior.

Depends-On: I8cc198bd1081e0c1864228dad6228daa92ac32b7
Related-Bug: #1676373

Add chrooted to the common vars

When building images from a container, the chrooted option
needs to be extended for the extras repos as well.
Make it shared via the common defaults.

Required-By: Ie880a33fbb758240638178c45c43156e80bf4d24

commit_message:
Add handler when systemd is used

The service handler will restart a sysV or upstart init script when
present instead of a systemd service unit. In Xenial both upstart and
systemd service files can be present at the same time which can create
an unintended consequence by restarting the wrong service. This change
creates a guard so that if systemd is used we restart using a systemctl
command otherwise we use the service module.

> NOTE a systemctl command is used because the systemd module is not
  available until ansible 2.2

Change-Id: I71cd03ac0f10e88e83c085b7a87b7b2f710d0c3e
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
bootstrap-host: Prepare disk for machinectl storage

Currently we prepare an available secondary disk, but do not
use it. The preparation taking place now was useful when the
backing file system for LXC was 'dir', but it is now machinectl
which uses a btrfs partition instead.

This patch implements the preparation of a btrfs sparse file
if there is no secondary disk, or the preparation of a secondary
btrfs disk if there is one.

The user_variables override for lxc_host_machine_volume_size
is removed as the default value in the role is perfectly adequate
for AIO deployment needs.

We also add some diagnostic information to help troubleshoot
issues if they arise.

Change-Id: Icadbcfd420bbe7c14a04606790cab09a1dce03ce

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-03-14 13:04:09.000000000', 'message': "Rearrange cell mapping tasks

Existing instances can be mapped to a newly created cell immediately
after the cell is created and by the same conductor host that created
the cell.

After a new compute host is built, it will need to mapped to a cell
through the 'discover_hosts' command of nova-manage. This command will
still need to be run against a host that has direct database access, but
the command is able to handle mapping of all compute hosts that do not
currently belong to the cell so it only needs to be run once per play.

There can be a short delay in the time between a compute service
starting and becoming available to be discovered and mapped but, for
most deployments, compute host discovery will be handled automatically
as a periodic task.

Conflicts:
>------tasks/main.yml

Change-Id: I4f7328e1aff79eb94f278999b97fbad8f44c6a3e
Closes-Bug: 1749037
Related-Bug: 1729661
Related-Bug: 1752540
(cherry picked from commit 6321cf90304023c20dc6abb87e2fa20107b7051d)
"}]
commit_message:
Rearrange cell mapping tasks

Existing instances can be mapped to a newly created cell immediately
after the cell is created and by the same conductor host that created
the cell.

After a new compute host is built, it will need to mapped to a cell
through the 'discover_hosts' command of nova-manage. This command will
still need to be run against a host that has direct database access, but
the command is able to handle mapping of all compute hosts that do not
currently belong to the cell so it only needs to be run once per play.

There can be a short delay in the time between a compute service
starting and becoming available to be discovered and mapped but, for
most deployments, compute host discovery will be handled automatically
as a periodic task.

Conflicts:
>------tasks/main.yml

Change-Id: I4f7328e1aff79eb94f278999b97fbad8f44c6a3e
Closes-Bug: 1749037
Related-Bug: 1729661
Related-Bug: 1752540
(cherry picked from commit 6321cf90304023c20dc6abb87e2fa20107b7051d)

commit_message:
Exclude api-ref changes from py checks

The style of the api-ref is to use template .rst files that pull
in some .inc and .yaml files. The current exclusion regex '^.*\.rst$'
doesn't capture these, so add a specific exclusion for the api-ref
directory.

Change-Id: If87734f04b2db8a829ebc6a81581b2cdac5a40fc
